<h2 class="rm-manual"> <a href="file:///news/pentagon-congress/">Pentagon &amp; Congress</a> </h2>
<h1 class="rm-manual">How a Kim Jong Un demise could spark unrest, require US, South Korean military response </h1>
<p class="rm-manual"> <span> <span><a href="file:///author/howard-altman" rel="author">Howard Altman</a></span> </span> </p>
<p class="rm-manual"> April 21 </p>
<figcaption class="rm-manual"> In this undated photo provided Nov. 25, 
2019, by the North Korean government, North Korean leader Kim Jong Un, 
center, poses as he inspects a women's company under Unit 5492 of the 
Korean People's Army in North Korea. (Korean Central News Agency/Korea 
News Service via AP) </figcaption><p> A<a href="https://www.militarytimes.com/training-sim/2020/03/30/north-korea-test-fires-missiles-amid-worries-about-outbreak/"> Kim Jong Un</a>
 demise could destabalize the region, create a massive refugee flow and 
force the U.S., South Korea and possibly other regional allies to react 
to the upheaval.</p>
<p> Thatâs how experts contacted by Military Times see a Kim-less future possibly unfolding in the nuclear-armed Hermit Kingdom.</p>
<p> The questions about what would happen should Kim die or be 
incapacitated were sparked by a CNN report that the North Korean despot 
was in â<a href="https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/20/politics/kim-jong-un-north-korea/index.html">grave danger</a>â
 following a surgery. However, the Yonhap News Agency, a South 
Korean-government funded organization, later tweeted out that there were
 âno unusual signsâ of Kimâs health.</p>
<p> But even if he isnât on his death bed, Kim does have health issues 
and his exit from the stage would create turmoil, experts say.</p>
<p> Without a designated heir there will be âchaos, human suffering, 
instability,â retired South Korean Lt. Gen. Chun In-Bum, the former head
 of his nationâs special operations forces, told Military Times. âItâs 
bad news for everyone.â</p>
<p> David Maxwell, a senior fellow at the Foundation for Defense of 
Democracies think tank who has two decades of military service in Asia 
said a U.S. and South Korean military reaction to that upheaval could 
require an effort that âwill make Afghanistan and Iraq pale in 
comparison."</p>
<p> Like Chun, Maxwell, a retired Special Forces colonel who served with
 him, said a lack of clear succession would set chaos into motion.</p>
<p> Kim Il Sung designated his son successor in 1973 and the Kim Il-sung designated his son success in 2009 or 2010.</p>
